Our work is concerned with the family $\nu:\mathrm{Hess}(\mathfrak{m})\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$
of Hessenberg varieties associated to a complex semisimple Lie algebra $\mathfrak{g}$ and its
standard Hessenberg subspace $\mathfrak{m}\subseteq\mathfrak{g}$. This family includes the
Peterson variety and certain smooth projective toric varieties, and it features prominently in
B\u{a}libanu's recent work. B\u{a}libanu considers a Kostant section $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathfrak{g}$
and a partially compactified universal centralizer $\overline{\mathcal{Z}_{\mathfrak{g}}}
\longrightarrow \mathcal{S}$, identifying the latter with $\nu^{-1}(\mathcal{S})$ as Poisson
varieties over $\mathcal{S}$. The Hessenberg variety over each $x\in\mathcal{S}$ is thereby
embedded into $\overline{G}$, the wonderful compactification of the adjoint group $G$. We examine
a distinguished class of Poisson transversals in log symplectic geometry -- the so-called Poisson
slices. This equips us to meaningfully study one such slice in the log cotangent bundle $T^*\overline{G}(\log(D))$.
The slice in question is a log symplectic Hamiltonian $G$-variety $\overline{\mu}:\overline{G\times\mathcal{S}}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$
that fibrewise compactifies the symplectic Hamiltonian $G$-variety $\mu:G\times\mathcal{S}
\longrightarrow\mathfrak{g}$. Our main result is then a canonical isomorphism $\mathrm{Hess}(\mathfrak{m})
\cong \overline{G\times\mathcal{S}}$ of Poisson varieties over $\mathfrak{g}$. The pullback
of our isomorphism to $\mathcal{S}$ is shown to be B\u{a}libanu's Poisson isomorphism, and we obtain
a canonical closed embedding $\nu^{-1}(x)\hookrightarrow\overline{G}$ for every $x\in\mathfrak{g}$.
